  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou1-accepted-2026-04-19",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/actor/lead-credibility-assessor",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team lead",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
    "rationale": "The CFD hemolysis prediction model for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump is accepted as credible for the declared COU at MRL 2. All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required Gradation 2 levels: (1) SQA confirmed via versioned commercial solver and unit-tested UDF; (2) code verification via MMS with OOA within 3% of formal order; (3) discretization error GCI < 3.2% on production mesh; (4) test conditions documented and within operating envelope for 3/5 target points; (5) output comparison within 11–17% at all experimentally covered points; (6) QoI (NIH, RH) directly maps to the regulatory acceptance criterion; (7) validation activities conducted on the identical geometry spanning 71% of the declared envelope. Six factors are appropriately scoped out or not-applicable at MRL 2, each with documented rationale. The two operating points lacking experimental hemolysis data (4 and 5) are bounded by the GCI-qualified CFD sensitivity sweep (VR-03); the resulting uncertainty does not alter the RH < 1.0 conclusion. The operating envelope is explicitly bounded (1–7 L/min, 1500–3500 RPM, five geometry tolerance variants ±0.05 mm), and the applicability constraint restricts use to adult CPB Class II centrifugal pumps of the FDA generic geometry family. No factor shortfall exists; no offset rationale is required. The structured evidence chain from foundational experimental data (FDA benchmark dataset) through mesh convergence, code verification, and output comparison is complete and traceable. The acceptance decision is grounded in the structured credibility evidence and is consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 requirements at MRL 2."
  },
